## Background Media — Always Remove Default Border-Radius

**Problem:** `Video` and `Image` components ship with rounded corners by default (`rounded-[6px]` on Video, `rounded-[8px]` on Image). When used as full-screen background layers (absolute, w-screen, h-screen), these rounded corners create visible clipped edges at the viewport boundary.

**Fix:** After placing any Video or Image as a full-screen absolute background layer, immediately call `set_border(nodeId, {radius: 0})`.

```ts
// ✅ After set_position(videoId, {position: "absolute", top: 0, left: 0, zIndex: 0})
set_border(videoId, { radius: 0 });  // remove default rounded-[6px]
```

**Rule:** The `aiRef` for Video and Image explicitly documents this requirement. It is enforced as a "Derived rule" in the builder system prompt — any tool that adds a Video or Image as a background layer must always pair it with `set_border({radius: 0})`.

## Hero Container — Remove Default Padding When All Children Are Absolute

**Problem:** Default Box/VStack templates ship with `p-[16px] gap-[16px]`. When a container's sole purpose is to stack absolute-positioned children (video layer, overlay layer, content layer), this padding creates invisible dead space that shifts the absolute coordinate origin.

**Fix:** After creating a container whose children will ALL be absolutely positioned, call `set_spacing(containerId, {p: 0, gap: 0})`.

**Rule:** Applies to hero section wrappers, full-screen overlay roots, and any container that only holds absolute children. Enforced as a "Derived rule" in the builder system prompt.
